		<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://www.the-reddot.com/2011/07/11/smooth-is-this-the-goddess-beauty/#comment-1523">
			July 12, 2011 at 5:24 pm</a>		</div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->

		<div class="comment-body"><p>@Faye and Luciana: the fact is this: I wasn&#8217;t talking ONLY about the kind of girls you&#8217;re talking about. </p>
<p>I&#8217;m talking about the ones that don&#8217;t need 350 euros and all of their time to look like that because they&#8217;re naturally like that, it&#8217;s genetics and it&#8217;s attitude and style, innate elegance. I used pictures of girls working in fashion because they were the most easy to find and the most &#8220;immediate&#8221; to deliver my idea.</p>
<p>But the women like that are also doctors that I see in the European hospitals where I work and where I attended meetings or congresses , lawyers that I saw in Florence, biomedical researchers like me (one of them, a Roman woman, she was just&#8230; I don&#8217;t know, she just leaves you breathless. And she was working an average of 11 hours a day in a lab like me, so I guess not much time for spa and beauty treatment)</p>
<p>Smoothness, as I call it, for them is a natural thing, almost an ability and it is something that I admire.</p>
<p>Luciana, from what you write it seems that if you spend money on your beauty and clothes then it means that you don&#8217;t spend enough time to be a nice and intelligent person.</p>
<p>My every day creams cost 250 euros all together. My routine make-up is made of pieces that go from 20 euros up. I spend 20 euros in a conditioner if I see that it makes a visible difference. Do I do it for someone? To look like someone? No, I do it because I like it.</p>
<p>But still I&#8217;ve got a master degree in Biotechnology and I&#8217;m taking my PhD in molecular virology, I work 10 hours a day (often in the week-ends and sometimes I have to study at night) but I still try to leave a piece of my brain and my time for these frivolous thing that make me feel good.</p>
<p>I don&#8217;t say that I don&#8217;t like myself, but I say that I admire them and I &#8220;use&#8221; their &#8220;smoothness&#8221; to continuously improve my aspects. This is because I think that it is stupid to passively accept how we are and, as a scientist who&#8217;s religion is the belief in progress and constant evolution, I think that pushing ourselves always to a higher target (of course in the limits of our possibilities) makes us become everyday better, being it at work, in our relationships or just in our wardrobe.</p>
<p>Ok, this comment is too long and I think that I&#8217;ll write a post on this topic later on because it is very interesting to have this kind of exchange of opinions</p>
<p>But let me tell you that the post was a bit ironic, too ;-) It was intended to be like one of those stupid chats that you have with your girlfriends for lunch, over a fashion magazine or some gossip and that make you laugh&#8230; I&#8217;m sad if I couldn&#8217;t explain myself properly :-(<br />
(LOL maybe it&#8217;s the result of the usual meltin&#8217; pot of the two languages, that makes me incapable of speaking both of them in a correct way? XD)</p>
<p>a big kiss to both of you and thanks for stopping to tell me your opinion, it was really food for thought :-*</p>
