		<div class="comment-body"><p>ahah thank you Anna!</p>
<p>Your comment reflects 100% my thought!!<br />
Just one thing: I still think that being thin (not super-thin, let&#8217;s say a normal but sleek figure) does a big part of the job. But as you said the way of walking and standing is even more important.<br />
The smoothest woman I&#8217;ve ever met is my grandmother: she wasn&#8217;t young (of course, when I was born and I first met her she was 60 :-p ), she wasn&#8217;t rich and she wasn&#8217;t the classic, extreme beauty (she even had a scar on her decolleté due to an old thyroid cancer) but she had the best character, style and overall looks ever.<br />
She was standing and walking like a princess, tall, straight and full of power. When she was talking she was looking at you straight in the eyes in the most charismatic way and she had a real talent to choose her outfits (a great sense of color, shape, quality/price ratio and knowledge of what suited her best&#8230; Even my mom, that still is a champion in this, is not that good).<br />
I can adore the looks of women like Taylor Tomasi as much as I want, but my grandma is the only one I really want to look like (and this time I have genetics on my side ;D)</p>
<p>But the ballet&#8230; I&#8217;m in the same condition dear: did ballet for 11 years and I still don&#8217;t walk walk exactly like a cat :D </p>
<p>The thing of the hair&#8230; Is so true!! In fact I have two rules:<br />
a) Only my hyper favorite hairdresser (recently found, she is perfection) in Italy can touch my hair<br />
b) Money spent on good hair products are worth it</p>
<p>These are two of my untouchable staples (another couple is to always spend in good products for the face and to always have a nice perfume, but not too strong)</p>
<p>A big kiss my dear</p>
</div>

